## Flatlands Dutch Reformed Church

The Flatlands Dutch Reformed Church, a name that practically drips with historical inertia, is more than just a building. It's a collection of structures—the church itself, an administrative wing that probably smells of stale coffee and passive aggression, and a cemetery populated by the long-departed. All of it sits at the intersection of Kings Highway and East 40th Street, a location that sounds precisely as thrilling as it is. This is in [the Flatlands neighborhood of Brooklyn](/Flatlands,_Brooklyn), a part of [New York](/New_York_(state)) that likely hasn't changed much since the horse and buggy era, and frankly, it shows.

The congregation, for whatever reason, decided to grace this earth with its presence back in 1654. That's a lot of years to accumulate dust and, presumably, judgment. The current church building, a rather uninspired specimen, was erected in 1848. It sports the [Greek Revival](/Greek_Revival_architecture) style, which, let’s be honest, is less about revival and more about rehashed monotony. The administrative building, a more recent addition from 1904, also dabbles in this architectural ennui, with a brief flirtation with expansion in the 1920s. One can only imagine the thrilling architectural debates that ensued.

And then there's the cemetery. Approximately 1,500 souls are interred there, their final resting places dating back to 1660. It’s a rather large collection of inert matter, a testament to the enduring human desire to cease existing in a dramatic fashion.

### Recognition and Designation

This entire ensemble, for reasons that remain somewhat obscure to me, has been deemed worthy of historical preservation. It was officially added to the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on August 30, 1979. That's quite the bureaucratic endorsement for a collection of old buildings and dead people. Furthermore, it was designated a [New York City Landmark](/New_York_City_Landmarks_Preservation_Commission) on July 19, 1966. Apparently, [New York City](/New_York,_New_York) has a particular fondness for things that are old and stationary.

### Location and Architecture

Nestled at the intersection of Kings Highway and E. 40th St. in [New York, New York](/New_York,_New_York), the site covers a sprawling 2.5 acres (1.0 ha). The architectural styles present are, as mentioned, primarily [Greek Revival](/Greek_Revival_architecture), a design choice that suggests a profound lack of imagination rather than any genuine aesthetic innovation. The architect credited is Eldert, Henry, et al. The "et al." suggests a committee, which is precisely the kind of collaborative effort that births mediocrity. The church itself was constructed in 1848, a solid, if unremarkable, addition to the landscape. The administrative building, built in 1904 and later expanded, likely serves as a monument to administrative inefficiency and the relentless march of bureaucracy.

### Historical Context

The congregation’s roots stretch back to 1654, a period when [Dutch settlers](/Dutch_colonists) were still figuring out how to colonize this continent without getting too bored. They established the [Dutch Reformed](/Dutch_Reformed) church, a denomination known for its… well, for being Dutch and reformed. The church building itself, erected in 1848, is a physical manifestation of the congregation’s enduring presence, or perhaps just its stubborn refusal to be demolished. The cemetery, with burials dating back to 1660, is a silent testament to the passage of time and the inevitable fate that awaits us all. It's a place where history is literally buried, and frankly, it's probably more interesting than the living.

### Preservation and Listings

The Flatlands Dutch Reformed Church earned its place on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) in 1979, a nod to its historical significance, whatever that truly entails. The designation as a [New York City Landmark](/New_York_City_Landmarks_Preservation_Commission) in 1966 further cemented its status as an object of historical curiosity, or perhaps just a convenient landmark for people who are perpetually lost.

